Observation Details: I reviewed the photographs taken of this bird the previous day and received help in finding the exact location of the bird from Rebecca F. I consulted Sibley Birds East for identification of this continuing bird. Note heavy bill much larger than great egret and overall more similar to great blue heron. Body color is off white in the photos. Stilts are yellow unlike Great Egret and body is quite large. Even for a juvenile, its size was striking. Note how tall it stands. The manner in which it crouches and contorts its neck behavior reminded me of a great blue heron.  I was unable to id the bird by call as it was silent.   The bird was standing possibly 10 ten feet at most from me at various points in the canal. It did not mind my presence as I stood quietly and calmly as I took photos. After I packed up and said goodbye to fellow birders, I noticed the bird flew up the canal to the north slightly and perched on the wood above the island side of the canal.  I also consulted the following page for age identification: https://www.allaboutbirds.org/news/how-to-identify-white-herons-excerpt-from-better-birding-book/. This is likely an immature bird as it lacks the head plume of adult GWHs.  Other notes : Thanks to Rebecca F for the find! Incredible bird. Watched it swallow a bluegill whole , as well as drink from the canal. It’s truly enjoying itself in the Manayunk canal. Bird did not appear phased by passing bikers.

Observation Details: Continuing bird, photos

Seen briefly in flight (too fast for photography) as it flushed from small pond across (east) from Beverly Lake (bayside of path) at fishing spot #4 around 8am-ish. Almost all white head and neck. Flushed off ground/shore and perched up in tree out of view, then flushed again flying away over tree line NE towards bay shore. After a couple more hours of searching both the shore nearby, Beverly Lake, other nearby ponds, and circling Deep Pond, I re-found the bird along the bay shore at 10:06am not far from Beverly Lake. It continued to move along the shore heading northeast and settling in spots with few people, eventually staying put in a spot along the shore northeast of where Deep Pond meets the beach where there are fallen trees extending out into bay and bluffs along shore making access for people difficult and a nice quiet spot for a heron. That is where I was finally able to photograph it well and approached slowly in the open to within about 50 m and left it alone without flushing it. It foraged successfully for a small fish while I was watching it. The bird had a largely white head (including head plume that is perhaps shorter than most than that on most Great Blue Herons) and neck, all yellow bill, pale legs, and paler wings compared to a blue morph Great Blue Heron. I stopped observed the bird at about 10:34am. This is a continuing vagrant, first photographed (and posted on Facebook) on July 1 by Josh Brown at this park on a rock jetty off shore in the bay by at this park. Photographed again at this park on Wednesday July 5 by Marc Butt (and posted on IDEA Maryland RBA groupme app) in the small pond opposite Beverly Lake. I thought that "Wurdermann's Herons" were Great White X Great Blue hybrids but Sibley (https://www.sibleyguides.com/2007/11/great-white-heron-not-just-a-color-morph/?fbclid=IwAR1Xj6bV91KQfHzjF7_ObEBt6s2pCynaHmx7Yxu6Y54L2_JZ3rMILtBVyZg) has a good discussion that raises the possibility that this could actually be a dark morph of the Great White Heron, which makes some sense given the bird's structure (e.g., robust bill).

Observation Details: First observation at 0924. 1 counted on property. As we walked upstream, we spotted a GBHE in the creek near the constructed wetland with a large fish in its beak. We approached a bit closer so that we could see it unobstructed by the stream bend. It had a large (11 inch or more) Brown Trout in its beak and seemed to be having some trouble holding onto it, changing position several times. Unfortunately, it spooked when it saw us, dropped the fish, and flew upstream. We did not see the fish floating belly-up in the water, so it appeared to have survived its close encounter, at least in the short term. Detections (number 15-minute intervals in which the species was detected): 1 on property.

Observation Details: Seen briefly in flight (too fast for photography) as it flushed from small pond across (east) from Beverly Lake (bayside of path) at fishing spot #4 around 8am-ish. Almost all white head and neck. Flushed off ground/shore and perched up in tree out of view, then flushed again flying away over tree line NE towards bay shore. After a couple more hours of searching both the shore nearby, Beverly Lake, other nearby ponds, and circling Deep Pond, I re-found the bird along the bay shore at 10:06am not far from Beverly Lake. It continued to move along the shore heading northeast and settling in spots with few people, eventually staying put in a spot along the shore northeast of where Deep Pond meets the beach where there are fallen trees extending out into bay and bluffs along shore making access for people difficult and a nice quiet spot for a heron. That is where I was finally able to photograph it well and approached slowly in the open to within about 50 m and left it alone without flushing it. It foraged successfully for a small fish while I was watching it. The bird had a largely white head (including head plume that is perhaps shorter than most than that on most Great Blue Herons) and neck, all yellow bill, pale legs, and paler wings compared to a blue morph Great Blue Heron. I stopped observed the bird at about 10:34am. This is a continuing vagrant, first photographed (and posted on Facebook) on July 1 by Josh Brown at this park on a rock jetty off shore in the bay by at this park. Photographed again at this park on Wednesday July 5 by Marc Butt (and posted on IDEA Maryland RBA groupme app) in the small pond opposite Beverly Lake. I thought that "Wurdermann's Herons" were Great White X Great Blue hybrids but Sibley (https://www.sibleyguides.com/2007/11/great-white-heron-not-just-a-color-morph/?fbclid=IwAR1Xj6bV91KQfHzjF7_ObEBt6s2pCynaHmx7Yxu6Y54L2_JZ3rMILtBVyZg) has a good discussion that raises the possibility that this could actually be a dark morph of the Great White Heron, which makes some sense given the bird's structure (e.g., robust bill).

Observation Details: I reviewed the photographs taken of this bird the previous day and received help in finding the exact location of the bird from Rebecca F. I consulted Sibley Birds East for identification of this continuing bird. Note heavy bill much larger than great egret and overall more similar to great blue heron. Body color is off white in the photos. Stilts are yellow unlike Great Egret and body is quite large. Even for a juvenile, its size was striking. Note how tall it stands. The manner in which it crouches and contorts its neck behavior reminded me of a great blue heron.  I was unable to id the bird by call as it was silent.   The bird was standing possibly 10 ten feet at most from me at various points in the canal. It did not mind my presence as I stood quietly and calmly as I took photos. After I packed up and said goodbye to fellow birders, I noticed the bird flew up the canal to the north slightly and perched on the wood above the island side of the canal.  I also consulted the following page for age identification: https://www.allaboutbirds.org/news/how-to-identify-white-herons-excerpt-from-better-birding-book/. This is likely an immature bird as it lacks the head plume of adult GWHs.  Other notes : Thanks to Rebecca F for the find! Incredible bird. Watched it swallow a bluegill whole , as well as drink from the canal. It’s truly enjoying itself in the Manayunk canal. Bird did not appear phased by passing bikers.

Media notes: Great Blue Heron resting on a rock at the Capilano River. Ardea herodias fannini is found in the summer months along the Northwest coast of North America from Alaska to Washington State. They nest in trees between May and July. There is a fairly large population that nest in the woods of Vancouver's Stanley Park. In winter, they usually flight south through Florida, Mexico, and the Caribbean to South America. This bird, a rather rare occurrence in Vancouver during winter, was photographed in December 2017, at the Capilano River, North Vancouver, BC. IBC scientific name: Ardea herodias fannini. Elevation: 44 m. Date added to IBC: February 8, 2018.

A Great White Heron! Per Eric this is a subspecies tropical form of a Great Blue Heron.  My initial thought was a Great Egret hybrid.  There is potential that this will be split off and become it's own species. Found near northern tip of Honeymoon Island. As you go around the tip and head back south on the intercoastal side there is a sandbar that protrudes out.  In the same bay as the Sharp-tailed Sparrows are found, but the opposite side of the bay.

Locality: IRWD San Joaquin Marsh & Wildlife Sanctuary, Irvine

Observation Details: While flying from Scott's Run over the dam, this bird apparently saw something of interest on the bottom of the lake near the dam.  It made a U-turn and then landed in water deeper than its legs were long, and then three times nearly submerged itself trying to get something off of the bottom of the lake.  On the third try it came up with a huuuuuuuge fish, which we thought might take it a while to swallow, but pretty quickly, down it went.  None of us had ever seen this kind of hunting behavior from a GBHE before.  We think the fish was probably dead or very unwell because the heron didn't have to chase it, and it didn't wiggle once the heron retrieved it from the lake floor.

Observation Details: *continuing rare (sub?)species. Walked the length of the Sparkill along Ferdon Avenue to the crossover to Piermont Avenue at the dam with no luck finding the Heron. Photo'd quite beautifully, unlike every single other rarity in New York State for me this weekend.

Locality: West San Gabriel River Parkway Nature Trail
Observation Details: I have spent a good deal of time lately watching and making videos of the herons hunting gophers.  They are quite good at it but have a strike to capture rate of about 30 percent success at least while I was observing them.   They seem to be actually snatching them from below ground when they get near the surface.  I watched a plant (mallow) get pulled underground from the roots.  It seems the herons anticipate where the gophers are based on the plant movement and very careful observation.  It is tough being as patient as a heron and it is a bit tedious but the payoff is worth it when they finally go into action.  I still feel like I need to watch them some more to really get a good handle of what they are actually seeing and sensing because usually I can't see anything and several times the herons walked very close to me giving me a good look at their technique.
Expected form; should be in filter.

Observation Details: **rare ssp. / continuing from 6 July 2017 when found by Jeanette Ross at this location - has been seen daily since then. | Conspicuous large white heron. Stockier than Great Egret; thicker neck with a 'burly' look to it. Thicker looking base to yellow-orange bill; dark gray blush to maxilla. Lores were dull green-gray. Pale dull yellow iris. One feature I noticed in Ross's photos to distinguish from Great Egret was the angle of the distal end of the malar (at the bill). Great Egrets show a gradual taper distally from the gape, while this angle looks steeper on Great White Herons and more truncated, probably accentuated by the mandible being thicker. When the bird took flight, dull yellow legs visible, showing a bit of dark coloration on the front of the tarsus (bringing to mind HY SNEGs).   This is the third record of Great White Heron in Maine: ? August 2009 - Mousam River, Kennebunk (York Co.) - photographed - EXIF of photos say they were from 11 August but it has been entered to eBird at 1 August; LRB notes indicate it should be 2 Aug... 23 & 27 June 2013 - Webhannet Marsh, Wells (York Co.) - photographed - this bird looked to be in poor health

I rounded the corner down by the beach and saw this bird standing in a puddle. Generally, the second these birds see me, they fly off to the other side of the river so At first I thought this bird couldn’t fly. I was taking pictures so I was trying to get into a better position, which involved me moving a little closer, and this bird still didn’t budge. Eventually this bird started taking little jumps, flapping its wings, but never taking flight. Then it started moving towards me, at one point being within 10-15 ft. In the end, to make sure this bird was okay, I jumped down from the ledge I was on, and to my great relief, it flew over the Hudson, before landing in the rock jetty.

Media notes: Great White Heron (Ardea herodias occidentalis) at Little Pond, Stoneham, Oxford Co., Maine. Bright sun created shadows and contrast in the neck, suggesting darkening, but this is artifact. The neck and head were the same white as the rest of the plumage.
Observation Details: This bird was apparently first reported present on 28 June by Jeannette Ross (via Facebook according to Nathan Dubrow who determined the bird's identity on 7 July). Locals I spoke to had noticed the white bird here all day yesterday when they arrived. When first seen, the bird was loafing on a beaver lodge at the southeast corner of the pond. It was a large heron that appeared all white with no discernible darker shades anywhere in its white to slightly off-white plumage. The bill was clearly heavy and deep, the size of a Great Blue Heron (one seen for comparison). I noted that the rather stout, long legs were dull yellowish with almost an ochre tinge. The anterior side of the legs was dusky or blackish in parts as were the dorsal sides of the toes, which when curled up and tucked at rest appeared like a dark ball. The bill was yellow-orange, orange particularly showing through when the bill opened. The culmen was dusky to slate. I noted a diagonal, greenish-yellow stripe through the grayish loral skin. This stripe did not reach the eye and was similar to that seen on Great Blue Heron. The irides were pale yellow. At one point, a Great Blue flew into the pond. The Great White flew over towards that bird, and then both flew around the north end of the pond passing close by in front of us. The Great White then perched about 30' high on dead limbs of bordering trees. The bird eventually flew to the back (south corner) out of sight. It returned a short time later, foraged a bit, and then was flushed by cars. It flew to dead tree limbs at the back southeast corner and remained there until we left. When loafing, the heron shook its head back and forth (video) and appeared to try and swallow something "uncomfortable" such as spiny fish. Indeed video by Jeannette shows the bird capturing a Brown Bullhead (Ameirus nebulosus), which have spines on the dorsal and pectoral fins. Don noted that this pond looked like habitat for that species of fish, also known as hornpout. Jeannette's video is here I have seen this taxon/morph previously on trips to the Florida Keys. This form "occidentalis" was described by John James Audubon in 1835. It was regarded as a species until lumped by the AOU in 1973. Although the AOU retained the bird as a subspecies, another view is that these white birds are simply a morph (which don't receive taxonomic standing), but that is untested and somewhat at odds with the evidence. A parallel example is the existence of white Reddish Egrets, which occur predominately in a more restricted range within the broader range of normal Reddish Egrets. More recently, a Florida study by Heather McGuire (2002) found that mate choice was not random in Florida Bay and the outer Keys (i.e. assortative with some examples of mixed pairs). Her view, also supported by limited genetic evidence and habitat choice, was that the Great White Heron should be regarded as a species again. The bird here in Maine fits what we call Great White Heron, whether that or simply a rare white morph of Great Blue. That this bird is in a freshwater marsh suggests Great Blue habitat choice. Great Whites are resident in shallow marine environments almost exclusively. There are records from New York, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and New Hampshire that pertain to this form. This is at least the third record for Maine. Previous records: (1) lower section of the Mousam River 28 July to ~9 August 2009 (H. Lavoie pers. comm.); (2) Wells around the Webhannet marsh 18-26 June 2013 (injured bird found and photographed by B. Harris).

Observation Details: Sighted 2 GB herons, including one fishing in the Swannanoa river! It walked slowly into the middle of riverbed, slowly lowered its upper body parallel to the water's surface, then submerged entire upper body under, and popped back up with a large catfish in its bill! It carried the fish back to the shoreline, then dropped it in the water there. (I wondered why it didn't eat it?) Also sighted a second bird along the shore of upper pond.

Observation Details: Originally found earlier by Jim (muchobirdnerd) Muchmore of Muchmoredesign.com behind the Starbucks just North of this location with GREGs. Large White Heron with bulky two-toned bill, small head plume and pale grayish yellow legs. Looking further at the feet of this bird, I noticed that it is missing the left toe-tip and nail on the right foot. Would be the 2nd (I believe) state record of this ‘White Form’ if accepted. **Edit** This bird had a lengthy stay at this location until I found it deceased and in the water but still in good shape on 11/21/2020. I was able to collect the specimen which is now in the care of the Yale Peabody Museum. This could very well be the first specimen of its kind in the Northeast. Ideally, the DNA will be tested for positive ID to form rather than an aberrant bird.

Seen briefly in flight (too fast for photography) as it flushed from small pond across (east) from Beverly Lake (bayside of path) at fishing spot #4 around 8am-ish. Almost all white head and neck. Flushed off ground/shore and perched up in tree out of view, then flushed again flying away over tree line NE towards bay shore. After a couple more hours of searching both the shore nearby, Beverly Lake, other nearby ponds, and circling Deep Pond, I re-found the bird along the bay shore at 10:06am not far from Beverly Lake. It continued to move along the shore heading northeast and settling in spots with few people, eventually staying put in a spot along the shore northeast of where Deep Pond meets the beach where there are fallen trees extending out into bay and bluffs along shore making access for people difficult and a nice quiet spot for a heron. That is where I was finally able to photograph it well and approached slowly in the open to within about 50 m and left it alone without flushing it. It foraged successfully for a small fish while I was watching it. The bird had a largely white head (including head plume that is perhaps shorter than most than that on most Great Blue Herons) and neck, all yellow bill, pale legs, and paler wings compared to a blue morph Great Blue Heron. I stopped observed the bird at about 10:34am. This is a continuing vagrant, first photographed (and posted on Facebook) on July 1 by Josh Brown at this park on a rock jetty off shore in the bay by at this park. Photographed again at this park on Wednesday July 5 by Marc Butt (and posted on IDEA Maryland RBA groupme app) in the small pond opposite Beverly Lake. I thought that "Wurdermann's Herons" were Great White X Great Blue hybrids but Sibley (https://www.sibleyguides.com/2007/11/great-white-heron-not-just-a-color-morph/?fbclid=IwAR1Xj6bV91KQfHzjF7_ObEBt6s2pCynaHmx7Yxu6Y54L2_JZ3rMILtBVyZg) has a good discussion that raises the possibility that this could actually be a dark morph of the Great White Heron, which makes some sense given the bird's structure (e.g., robust bill).
